5.0 Ethical Framework

5.1 Ethical Design Principles

The LIM implements five core ethical principles derived from international humanitarian law and just war theory:

Principle 1: Civilian Protection (Weight: 0.35)

· Civilian lives prioritized above all else
· Maximum acceptable civilian risk: 10%
· No engagement if civilian proximity <100m

Principle 2: Proportional Response (Weight: 0.25)

· Force must be proportional to threat
· Maximum force multiplier: 2.0x
· Consideration of alternative responses

Principle 3: Minimum Necessary Force (Weight: 0.20)

· Use minimum power required
· Precision targeting to minimize damage
· Efficiency threshold: 80%

Principle 4: System Preservation (Weight: 0.15)

· Protect system integrity within ethical bounds
· Self-defense within proportionality
· Recovery time <5 minutes

Principle 5: International Law Compliance (Weight: 0.05)

· Geneva Conventions adherence
· UN Charter compliance
· Customary international law

5.2 Civilian Protection Protocols

Multi-layer civilian protection mechanisms:

Layer 1: Detection and Identification

· Multi-spectral sensors distinguish combatants from civilians
· AI pattern recognition for civilian behavior
· Real-time population density mapping

Layer 2: Risk Assessment

· Probabilistic risk modeling
· Dynamic safety margin calculation
· Atmospheric effect consideration

Layer 3: Engagement Constraints

· Automatic stand-down if civilian risk >10%
· Minimum safe distance: 100m
· Maximum engagement angle constraints

Layer 4: Human Verification

· Lethal engagements require human confirmation
· Real-time video verification
· Multiple human operators for high-risk scenarios

5.3 Proportional Response Algorithms

The system calculates proportional responses using:

Threat Value Calculation:

```
TV = f(threat_type, velocity, altitude, payload, intent)
```

Required Response Calculation:

```
RR = TV × K × (1 - C) × A
```

Where:

· K: Kinetic factor (material properties)
· C: Civilian risk discount
· A: Atmospheric attenuation

Response Selection:

· Non-lethal options prioritized
· Graduated response escalation
· Continuous reassessment during engagement

5.4 International Law Compliance

The system maintains compliance through:

Legal Database Integration:

· Geneva Conventions database
· Additional Protocols
· Customary international law
· National implementation laws

Real-Time Legal Analysis:

· Situation classification (armed conflict, peacekeeping, etc.)
· Combatant status determination
· Military necessity evaluation
· Distinction principle application

